    {
      "id": "6ca1b7ae_a7f73fa7",
      "file_path": "docker_push_manifest.sh",
      "patchset_number": 2,
      "line": 2,
      "message": "I have a suggestion towards handling that, I added some comments in the pom.xml file + below.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 5695,
        "name": "Alexandru Avadanii",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "Alexandru.Avadanii@enea.com",
        "username": "AlexandruAvadanii"
      },
      "updated": "2019-08-27 17:28:04.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "00688af1_7a2074e9",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "fb27a7e8_971db168",
      "file_path": "docker_push_manifest.sh",
      "patchset_number": 2,
      "line": 8,
      "message": "The mechanism suggested in pom.xml would require something like this block (and of course moving the manifest tool download earlier in the script):\n\n  IMAGES=policy-base-alpine policy-common-alpine\n  ARCHES=amd64 aarch64\n  TIMESTAMP=$(date -u +\"%Y%m%d%H%M%S\")\n  for image in ${IMAGES}; do\n    for arch in ${ARCHES}; do\n      docker tag ${image}:latest-${arch} ${image}:${release_version}-${TIMESTAMP}-${arch}\n    done\n    # create a list of arch-agnostic tags based on preexisting amd64 tags by removing the suffix\n    TAGS=$(docker inspect ${image}:latest-amd64 --format '{{.RepoTags}}' | \\\n           grep -Po \":(\\K[^ ]*?)(?=-amd64)\")\n    for tag in ${TAGS}\n      ./docker_manifest.sh \"${image}\" \"${tag}\"\n      ./manifest-tool push from-spec \"${image}_${tag}.yaml\"\n    done\n  done",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 5695,
        "name": "Alexandru Avadanii",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "Alexandru.Avadanii@enea.com",
        "username": "AlexandruAvadanii"
      },
      "updated": "2019-08-27 17:28:04.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "dbbe33f1_cdd351b8",
      "file_path": "policy-base/alpine/pom.xml",
      "patchset_number": 2,
      "line": 84,
      "message": "Not needed for this image, as its Dockerfile works unchanged for any arch (upstream FROM image is multiarch-capable).\nHopefully we can drop the duplicate Dockerfiles for the other image too.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 5695,
        "name": "Alexandru Avadanii",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "Alexandru.Avadanii@enea.com",
        "username": "AlexandruAvadanii"
      },
      "updated": "2019-08-27 17:28:04.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "440405fe_e666cd18",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "84477a44_e5050148",
      "file_path": "policy-base/alpine/pom.xml",
      "patchset_number": 2,
      "line": 86,
      "message": "I would rework this mechanism + the one in the manifest push like this:\n\n  <tags>\n    <tag>${project.version}-${os.arch}</tag>\n    <tag>${project.docker.latesttag.version}-${os.arch}</tag>\n  </tags>\n\nNote that each old tag is suffixed with \"-${os.arch}\" and the timestamp-sensitive one is removed (since timestamps would be different across different build machines).\n\nSo the manifest push would now only have to deal with:\n- creating + pushing of arch-independent tags for each pair of arch-qualified tags found (that way we don't hardcode the list of tags in the manifest pushing script, but instead keep here / from version.properties);\n- tagging 'latest' with the timestamp-sensitive tag;\n\nIf we change it, other occurrences (e.g. in the manifest yaml) should be updated as well.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 5695,
        "name": "Alexandru Avadanii",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "Alexandru.Avadanii@enea.com",
        "username": "AlexandruAvadanii"
      },
      "updated": "2019-08-27 17:28:04.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "0d425587_5107c3d2",
      "file_path": "policy-common/alpine/pom.xml",
      "patchset_number": 2,
      "line": 85,
      "message": "see comment in Dockerfile.aarch64, I think we can drop this and use a single Dockerfile.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 5695,
        "name": "Alexandru Avadanii",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "Alexandru.Avadanii@enea.com",
        "username": "AlexandruAvadanii"
      },
      "updated": "2019-08-27 17:28:04.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "873152ae_277bbe8c",
      "file_path": "policy-common/alpine/src/main/docker/Dockerfile.aarch64",
      "patchset_number": 2,
      "line": 22,
      "message": "imo this should not be needed and the FROM should just resolve to the latest-aarch64 tag via the manifest (provided that the policy-base image has already been switched to using multiarch manifests).\nIf that works as intended, we no longer need 1 Dockerfile per arch and instead can reuse the same old Dockerfile for both builds.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 5695,
        "name": "Alexandru Avadanii",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "Alexandru.Avadanii@enea.com",
        "username": "AlexandruAvadanii"
      },
      "updated": "2019-08-27 17:28:04.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "ce8ab35a_15d48f52",
      "file_path": "policy-common/alpine/src/main/docker/Dockerfile.aarch64",
      "patchset_number": 2,
      "line": 22,
      "message": "I know it's odd, but maven resolves `os.arch` to amd64, respectively aarch64.\nUsually the platform is represented as x86_64/aarch64 or amd64/arm64, but `os.arch` is different.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 5695,
        "name": "Alexandru Avadanii",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "Alexandru.Avadanii@enea.com",
        "username": "AlexandruAvadanii"
      },
      "updated": "2019-08-27 17:28:04.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "b297139c_dc755b06",
      "unresolved": true
    },
